ss2star  aBeing a home to more than 80 ethnic groups, Ethiopia has to balance normative diversity with efforts to implement state law across its territory.This volume explores the co-existence of state, customary, and religious legal forums from the perspective of legal practitioners and local justice seekers. It shows how the various stakeholders' use of negotiation, and their strategic application of law can lead to unwanted confusion, but also to sustainable conflict resolution and innovative new procedures and hybrid norms. The book thus generates important knowledge on the necessary conditions for stimulating a cooperative co-existence between different legal systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aLegal polycentricityzEthiopia. 4aAfrica. 4aCultural Diversity. 4aCulture. 4aCustomary Law. 4aEthics. 4aEthiopia. 4aEthnology. 4aLaw. 4aNormative Orders. 4aSociology of Law. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aCultural Diversity.  aCulture.  aCustomary Law.  aEthics.  aEthiopia.  aEthnology.  aLaw.  aNormative Orders.  aSociology of Law.1 aAbdo, Mohammed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbdo, Muradu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbera, Melaku, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmsalu, Desalegn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssefa, Getachew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssefa, Getachew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDegefa, Aberra, econtributor.4ctb